Looking at the mutation more carefully:

- Original: `if (this._queue.size || this._inFlightWrites > 0)` - waits if queue has items OR there are in-flight writes
- Mutated: `if (this._queue.size && this._inFlightWrites > 0)` - only waits if BOTH conditions are true

The key scenario to expose: call `close()` when `_queue.size === 0` but `_inFlightWrites > 0`. After `_flush()` runs, items are removed from the queue but writes are still in-flight. So if we call `close()` right after `set()` (which triggers `_flush()`), the queue will be empty but writes are in-flight.

With the mutation, `close()` won't wait for drain and will immediately destroy the write stream. This means the `drain` event should fire before `write_close` in the original, but with the mutation, `write_close` may fire without `drain` ever firing.

